    <h1>Lentil Dhal</h1>
    <p>I've been making this yummy lentil dhal recipe   since I was a teenager. It comes from Rose Elliott's cookbook <i>Cheap and Easy</i>. I've included the creamed coconut, though it also tastes great without it. You can also make this in a soup maker, which makes things even easier!</p> 
    <img src="https://www.thespruceeats.com/thmb/uOLxhhppFWyR1iCM2Q3jrbaEGPA=/1500x0/filters:no_upscale():max_bytes(150000):strip_icc()/vegetarian-mung-dhal-recipe-3378496-hero-03-f1c34f2638ff46d9880130cda0c61e3e.jpg" alt="Lental dhal" width="500">
    <h2>Ingredients</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>250g red split lentils</li>
      <li>2 medium onions</li>
      <li>1 clove garlic</li>
      <li>2 tbsp olive oil or vegetable oil</li>
      <li>1 small piece ginger (approx 5g)</li>
      <li>1 tsp ground cumin</li>
      <li>1 tsp ground coriander</li>
      <li>1 tsp ground turmeric</li>
      <li>1/2 tsp chilli powder</li>
      <li>1/2 tsp salt</li>
      <li>800ml water or vegetable stock</li>
      <li>50g creamed coconut, grated</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2>Instructions</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>
        Chop the onion and crush the garlic.
      </li>
      <li>
        Fry the onion in the oil on a low-medium heat     for 5 minutes, stirring regularly.
      </li>
      <li>
        Add the crush garlic and fry for 2-3 minutes, stirring regularly.
      </li>
      <li>
        Add the lentils, cumin, coriander, chilli powder and salt, and fry for 1 minute, stirring continually.
      </li>
      <li>
        Add the water or stock, bring to the boil, and simmer for 20 minutes, until the lentils are soft and the mixture starts to thicken.
      </li>
      <li>
        Turn off the heat and add the creamed coconut. Stir until the creamed coconut has mixed in. 
      </li>
      <li>
        Serve with rice or chapatis. 
      </li>
    </ol>
